Here's a practical path to becoming a Linux kernel expert:
  
  1. Foundations
  
  - Master C (pointers, memory management, bitwise ops)
  - Learn computer architecture: CPU modes, MMU, caches, interrupts
  - Read "Linux Kernel Development" by Robert Love as your first book
  
  2. Build & Run
  
  - Compile your own kernel from source, tweak configs
  - Use QEMU/VMs to test without bricking your machine
  - Learn to read boot logs and use dmesg
  
  3. Read the Source
  
  - Start with a subsystem you care about (networking, filesystems, drivers)
  - Use cscope/ctags or elixir.bootlin.com to navigate
  - Read commit messages — they explain why, not just what
  
  4. Write Code
  
  - Write a simple kernel module (char device, proc entry)
  - Pick "good first issue" bugs from the kernel bugzilla
  - Submit trivial cleanups to staging drivers to learn the patch submission process
  
  5. Deep Dive
  
  - Study one subsystem thoroughly (scheduler, memory manager, VFS, networking stack)
  - Read "Understanding the Linux Kernel" (Bovet & Cesati) or "Linux Device Drivers" (Corbet et al.)
  - Follow LKML discussions in your area of interest
  
  6. Debug & Trace
  
  - Learn ftrace, perf, eBPF, kprobes
  - Use KASAN, UBSAN, lockdep to find bugs
  - Practice crash dump analysis with kdump/crash
  
  7. Contribute
  
  - Subscribe to a subsystem mailing list
  - Review others' patches — you learn faster reading than writing
  - Aim for progressively more complex fixes and features
  
  Key mindset shifts:
  
  - The kernel has no libc, no exceptions, no safety net — every byte matters
  - Read more code than you write, especially early on
  - Pick one subsystem and go deep rather than skimming everything
  - It takes years — consistency beats intensity


##########
MMU & Virtual Memory
  
  - Page tables: 4-level (PGD → PUD → PMD → PTE) on x86_64, each entry is 8 bytes with flags (present, writable, user, NX)
  - TLB: Translation cache, TLB flushes are expensive — kernel batches them (flush_tlb_range)
  - Page faults: Hardware triggers #PF → kernel decides: allocate page, swap in, copy-on-write, or segfault
  - Huge pages: 2MB/1GB pages reduce TLB misses for large allocations
  - KASLR/KPTI: Security uses of page tables (kernel page table isolation against Meltdown)
  
  Study: Trace a virtual address through /proc/<pid>/pagemap, read the page table walk code in arch/x86/mm/.
  
  Caches
  
  - L1/L2/L3 hierarchy: L1 ~1ns, L2 ~5ns, L3 ~15ns, RAM ~80ns
  - Cache lines: Typically 64 bytes — misaligned data structures cause extra cache line fetches
  - Cache coherency: MESI/MOESI protocols across cores, false sharing when two CPUs write to the same cache line
  - Kernel implications:
    - ____cacheline_aligned attribute for hot structures
    - Per-CPU data avoids cache bouncing
    - likely()/unlikely() hints affect instruction cache prefetch
    - RCU exists partly because of cache costs of locking
  
  Study: Use perf stat to measure L1/LLC cache miss rates, then optimize a data structure to fix them.
  
  Interrupts
  
  - Hardware interrupts (IRQ): Device signals CPU via interrupt controller (APIC on x86), CPU jumps to IDT entry
  - Top half vs bottom half: ISR does minimal work (ack hardware, queue work), deferred processing via softirqs/tasklets/workqueues
  - Softirqs: Fixed set (NET_RX, TIMER, etc.), run after hardware IRQs, can't sleep
  - Context: Interrupt context has no current->mm, limited stack (~8KB), can't call sleeping functions
  - IPI (inter-processor interrupt): One CPU pokes another for TLB shootdown, rescheduling, etc.
  - Interrupt affinity: /proc/irq/<n>/smp_affinity pins IRQs to specific cores
  
  Study: Write a driver that registers an interrupt handler, trace the flow with ftrace (irq_handler_entry).
  
